URL reference: https://www.kubernetes.dev/blog/2025/11/12/ingress-nginx-retirement/
DateReviewed: 2025-11-18
Description: Today's article is about the upcoming retirement of Ingress Nginx, and how to prepare for it. Basically it'll be maintained somewhat until March of 2026, but after that it won't get more releases or security updates at all. The main recommendation is to move to Gateway API, but they do note there are a number of other Ingress controller alternatives available. They dive a bit into Ingress and talk about how the Nginx Ingress controller was an early example with a lot of flexibilty and good independence from any paticular provider. Next we pivot to history and challenges, where they remark that early flexibility allowed configs that were considered security issues later on. One of the big hurdles was the small number of devs working on it, and the fact they moved from Nginx to the Gateway API as their main focus. We now land on current state and next steps, where the Kubernetes governance groups have decided to retire the project rather than keep encouraging people to use a project that is not actively maintained. They explain that the artifacts will be accessible, just not recommended to use. They include instructions on how to check if you are running it, and thanks to the maintainers for their efforts up until now.
BottomLine: Good overview of why Nginx Ingress is retiring from Kubernetes and what to do to prepare
