URL reference: https://huyenchip.com/2021/09/13/data-science-infrastructure
DateReviewed: 2025-11-20
Description: Today's article is about why Data Scientists don't need to know Kubernetes. The thesis here is that DataSci's should be focused on their stack, and not what their stack runs on, and can use a infra abstraction tool to avoid knowing what the underlying bits are doing. They post a couple of job ads, and talk about the expectation that DataSci people should be "full stack". It seems our author had a change of heart, expecting at first to know low-level infra, then pivoting to not have to worry about it. He frames the need to know things as the difference between dev and prod, where you might have different tools and langs, and different uses for the data itself. He says these are managed usually by a CI/CD process, which don't work well for DataSci. He talks about using containers, and also abstracting the underlying infra. My take is I understand where he's coming from, but honestly not having any understanding of the infra makes for worse understanding of flows and costs, and less ability to tune and take advantage of the latest advances in tech. Interesting perspective though.
BottomLine: Good thinkpiece on approaches to low-level infra on Kubernetes
==
URL reference: https://www.techzine.eu/news/security/136197/runtime-behind-docker-and-kubernetes-contains-three-vulnerabilities/
DateReviewed: 2025-11-21
Description: Our article today tackles some issue with runC, the runtime piece that underlies both Docker and Kubernetes containers. We start with background and the various CVE numbers, and pointing out this breaks seperation (or enables a container escape). The weakness is from allowing certain paths to be mounted inside the container with writer perms -- which allows attackers to change or overwrite files. The idea is for an attacker to create a symlink to the file he wants to control, and then use that as a mount which will allow whatever the attacker wants. They do note that this is now fixed, but that exploitable clusters are still out there in the wild.
BottomLine: Short overview of a runC vuln that works agaisnt Kubernetes and Docker
